('', '1', 1, 1, 1, 'avant', 'avant', 'preposiziun', 'preposition', 'ago', 'ago', 'avon', 'avon', 'avànt, davànt', 'avànt, davànt', 'avant', 'avant', 'avaunt', 'avaunt', 'avant', 'avant', 'Romansh: \"davant\"/\"avant\":\nThe use of \"davant\" and \"avant\" differs considerably between the various versions of Romansh. To keep things simple, the situation for the standardized language, Rumantsch Grischun, can be summarized as follows:\n(1) \"Davant\" is used as a preposition and adverb of place = \"in front\" / \"in front of\".\n(2) \"Avant\" is used primarily as a preposition and adverb of time = \"before\" / \"before(hand)\".\n(3) In certain circumstances, \"avant\" is used like \"davant\" - in the same way as \"before\" is sometimes used spatially in English too (\"before your very eyes\", etc.).\n(4) \"Avant\" is also used for \"ago\", but note that the expression of time comes after it  not before as in English.', '', '', '', '', 322),
