('', '1', 1, 1, 0, 'idiom', 'idiom', 'num masculin', 'noun', 'idiom', 'idiom', '(=RG)', 'idiom', '(=RG)', 'idiom', '(=RG)', 'idiom', '(=RG)', 'idiom', '(=RG)', 'idiom', 'Idiom:\n\"Idiom\" has maintained a meaning in Romansh that it has more or less lost in modern everyday English. It refers to regional varieties of a language. Romansh has five traditional idioms, which are both spoken and written forms of the language. An idiom is more than a dialect. The five traditional idioms of Romansh can be subdivided into about two dozen (spoken) dialects.\n\"Idiom\" in the usual English sense is best rendered by \"expressiun idiomatica\".', 'Idiom:\nEn englais vul \"idiom\" normalmain mo dir \"expressiun idiomatica\". Per resguardar il concept rumantsch dad \"idiom\" èsi meglier da dir insatge sco \"(traditional) regional variant\". Tar na-spezialist(a)s èsi probablamain meglier dad acceptar il pled \"dialect\" - forsa cun in\'agiunta, per exempel: \"a Romansh idiom is a bit more than a dialect\".', '', '', '', 387),
