('', '1', 1, 0, 1, 'laschar', 'laschar', 'verb', 'verb', 'leave, let, arrange for', 'leave, left, let', 'laschar', 'laschar, schar', 'schar, laschar', 'schar, laschar', 'lascher', 'lascher', 'lascher', 'lascher', 'laschar', 'laschar', 'Romansh verbs (2):\nRegular verbs with an infinitive in \"-ar\":\n\"Laschar\" is one of these. To view its full conjugation, click \"Details\".\n\"Lascher\" + a second verb in the infinitive is used in the sense of \"to let something be done\", \"to cause something to be done\", \"to have something done\" (cf. French, Italian, German, etc.).\nIn the spoken language, the first syllable, \"la\", is often omitted.', '', 'Schar construir ina chasa\n= \"have a house built\".', 'LASCHAR\n\nPreschent:\njau lasch\nti laschas\nel/ella/ins lascha\nnus laschain\nvus laschais\nels/ellas laschan\n\nFutur:\njau vegn a laschar\nti vegns a laschar\nel/ella/ins vegn a laschar\nnus vegnin a laschar\nvus vegnis a laschar\nels/ellas vegnan a laschar\n\nImperfect:\njau laschava\nti laschavas\nel/ella/ins laschava\nnus laschavan\nvus laschavas\nels/ellas laschavan\n\nParticip perfect:\nlaschà (f: laschada, mpl: laschads, fpl: laschadas)\n\nPerfect:\njau hai laschà\nti has laschà\nel/ella/ins ha laschà\nnus avain laschà\nvus avais laschà\nels/ellas han laschà\n\nCundiziunal:\njau laschass\nti laschassas\nel/ella/ins laschass\nnus laschassan\nvus laschassas\nels/ellas laschassan\n\nConjunctiv:\nche jau laschia\nche ti laschias\nch\'el/ella/ins laschia\nche nus laschian\nche vus laschias\nch\'els/ellas laschian\n\nImperativ:\nlascha!\nlaschai!\n\nGerundi:\nlaschond', '', 3463),
('', '', 0, 0, 1, 'laschar encrescher', 'laschar encrescher', 'verb', 'verb', 'homesickness: feel homesick, suffer homesickness', 'homesick', 'schar encrescher', 'schar encrescher', 'schar ancrescher', 'schar ancrescher', 'lascher ancrescher', 'lascher ancrescher', 'as lascher increscher', 'as lascher increscher', 'as laschar increscher', 'as laschar increscher', 'Homesickness, longing for home:\nA longing to be back home is at the heart of Romansh feelings and is reflected in numerous writings and songs.\nAsking travellers if they long to be home or if they feel homesick is almost as much a part of Romansh conversation as is the weather in the English-speaking world!\nThe subject of \"encreschadetgna\" is not new. It has roots deep in history. In the poor regions of Romansh-speaking Graubünden the rural economy was only ever able to support a limited population, and many people simply had to go elsewhere for a period of time or even for good to find the merest of livelihoods.\nNote the verbal expression \"Laschas ti encrescher?\" (\"Do you feel homesick?\" - literally: \"do you allow a feeling of homesickness to arise?\")\n(See also the note on \"swallow\" or \"randulin(a)\".)', '', '', '', '', 3464),
