('', '', 0, 0, 1, 'trair endament, far endament', 'trair endament, far endament', 'verb', 'verb', 'remind, recall', 'remind, recall', 'far endamen', 'far endamen', 'far andamaint', 'far andamaint', 'far andamaint', 'far andamaint', 'trer adimmaint', 'trer adimmaint', 'trar adimmaint', 'trar adimmaint', 'Remember, recall, remind, recollect:\nIn Romansh, \"regurdar\" is used for recalling something or reminding someone else of something and \"sa regurdar\" is used for remembering something oneself.\n\"Trair endament\" / \"far endament\" is a more elegant expression for \"remind\" / \"recall\"\nNote also the very common use in Romansh of \"savair anc\" for \"remember\" (literally \"still know\", i.e. not to have forgotten).\n\"Memorisar\" is used for remembering in the sense of committing to memory.', 'Regurdar, sa regurdar, savair anc:\nIls different terms en englais chaschunan savens problems:\n\"Remember\" è il pled normal per \"sa regurdar\".\n\"Recollect\" è in term pli elegant per \"sa regurdar\".\n\"Remind\" è il pled normal per \"regurdar\" (trair endament, far endament).\n\"Recall\" po vegnir duvrà per \"sa regurdar\" e \"regurdar\".\nFar attent al diever: \"Let me remind you of what happened\" u \"Let me recall what happened for you.\"\nEn englais na datti nagin\'expressiun che correspundess directamain a \"savair anc\".', '', '', '', 6915),
('', '', 0, 0, 0, 'trair favugn', 'trair favugn', 'expressiun verbala', 'verbal expression', '* Guardar las Remartgas. *\n* See Comments. *', 'föhn', 'trer favugn', 'trer favugn', 'trer favugn', 'trer favugn', 'favugnier (trer favogn)', 'favugnier, favogna, trer favogn', 'ad es favuogn', 'favuogn', 'trar favuogn', 'trar favuogn', 'Favugn, föhn:\nThe \"föhn\" or \"favugn\" is a hot downwind. This weather phenomenon is caused when a wet wind cools slowly as it ascends the Alps, loosing its precipitation, and then warms up again much faster as it descends in a drier state. It is blamed for all sorts of disorders affecting people and animals.\nThe usual Romansh expression is \"i trai favugn\" (= \"there\'s a föhn blowing\").\nComplication:\nThe word \"fö(h)n/favugn\" is sometimes also used in Romansh and German to mean \"hair dryer\"!', '', '', '', '', 6916),
('', '', 0, 0, 0, 'trair schibettas', 'trair schibettas', '..', '..', '* Guardar las Remartgas. *\n* See Comments. *', '', 'trer schibettas', 'trer schibettas', 'trer schibetas', 'trer schibetas', 'trer schebas', 'trer schebas', 'tir a schaibgias', 'tir a schaibgias', 'tir a schaibgias', 'tir a schaibgias', 'Graubünden customs:\nThis was once a widespread custom in Switzerland. It is believed that it was originally a courtship/fertility rite. A few villages still practise it today, including Dardin, Danis and Tavanasa in Surselva.\nAfter nightfall on the Saturday following Ash Wednesday, the young men gather above the village and light a big bonfire. They heat up discs of elm wood (\"schibettas\"), which somewhat resemble modern frisbees with a small hole in the middle. When these are red hot, they are taken out of the fire on thin sticks and hurled though the air down the valley, flying considerable distances. As it is thrown, each schibetta is dedicated to one of the young women of the village. The thrower shouts out her name. Whilst this is going on, the young women of the village make special large biscuits (\"patlaunas\"), which they share with the young men when they return from their exertions.', '', '', '', '', 6917),
